        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The CO(2-1) line is redshifted to 91.41GHz for z=1.522, accessible to the Band 3 receivers. A single 1.875GHz baseband covers ~6000km/s at this frequency, and easily encompasses the expected line width. We configure the correlator to cover the maximum 1.875GHz bandwidth, and request spectral averaging by a factor of 16x, resulting in a velocity resolution of 25km/s. As this is much narrower than the expected line width, this allows us flexibility in later spectral averaging. We tune the second baseband to cover the redshifted HCN(3-2) line at 105.4GHz. This line is not expected to be detected unless C21434 contains significantly more molecular gas than expected. In that case, having simultaneous observations of the HCN(3-2) line can constrain the fraction of molecular gas that is in a dense, likely actively star-forming phase. As this observation can be placed with no additional overhead or observing time, it is prudent and scientifically useful to observe this line simultaneously with our primary target, CO(2-1).</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>C21434 is very compact in near-IR imaging, with an effective radius of ~2kpc (&lt;0.25" at z~1.5). It is infeasible to attempt to spatially resolve the source before initially detecting it in CO(2-1). Thus, we request the most compact array configuration possible, C36-1. At the frequency of these observations, this corresponds to a resolution of approximately 3.5". As the source is extremely compact, the largest angular scale is expected to be &lt;&lt;2". We expect this source to be pointlike for any configuration up to C36-4, allowing it to be scheduled easily during times when higher frequency observing is not possible.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>From optical spectroscopy, the dispersion in C21434 is approximately 600km/s. It is possible that the line width from CO will be less than this value, and so we adopt 300km/s as our bandwidth used in sensitivity calculations. If the line is as broad as the stellar line profiles, this will allow us to spectrally resolve the CO(2-1) line. As this is a pure detection experiment, however, we do not require a large number of velocity bins across the line to achieve our scientific goals; as such, a bandwidth for sensitivity of 300km/s is justified.

We estimate our required sensitivity through a variety of means, driven by our objective to detect molecular gas in this galaxy. We have calculated the expected gas mass of C21434 by comparing the dynamical and stellar masses, by considering the gas fraction evolution with specific star formation rate (Figure 3a), and by assuming C21434 falls on the Kennicutt-Schmidt relation between star formation rate and gas surface density for quiescent galaxies (Figure 4a). Of these methods, the most pessimistic is that the galaxy falls in the empirical scatter below the relation between gas fraction and specific star formation rate, so we proceed under this assumption. The other methods all predict larger gas masses and would result in stronger detections. We make use the CO-H2 conversion factor predicted from the theoretical work of Narayanan et al. (2012). We assume a CO line ratio of r_21 = 0.5 in brightness temperature units, typical of non-star-forming gas and likely a lower limit to the true CO(2-1) luminosity. Based on the scatter in the relationship between gas fraction and specific star formation rate (Figure 3a), we aim to reach a minimum 3sigma detection threshold corresponding to a gas fraction of Mgas/(Mstar + Mgas) = 0.04, or log(Mgas/Msun) = 9.87. With our adopted CO(2-1)/CO(1-0) line ratio and CO-H2 conversion factor, this corresponds to a sensitivity of 250uJy per 300km/s velocity bin. We re-emphasize that this sensitivity calculation is intentionally pessimistic, and any changes to our assumptions would only increase the significance of our detection and our ability to spectrally resolve the line.

We note that we do not expect to detect continuum at any significant level.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
